1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:16,000
 Welcome to C Programming for Everybody. My name is Charles Severance and this is my reading of the 1978 C programming book written by Brian Kernigan and Dennis Ritchie. At times, I add my own interpretation of the material from a historical perspective.

2
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:28,000
 Chapter 7, Input and Output. Input and output facilities are not part of the C language so we've de-emphasized them in our presentation thus far.

3
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:36,000
 Nonetheless, real programs do interact with their environment in much more complicated ways than those we've shown before.

4
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:44,000
 In this chapter, we will describe the standard IO library, a set of functions designed to provide a standard IO system for C programs.

5
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:54,000
 The functions are intended to present a convenient programming interface, yet reflect only operations that can be provided on most modern operating systems.

6
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:03,000
 The routines are efficient enough that users should seldom feel the need to circumvent them for efficiency regardless of how critical the application.

7
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:22,000
 Finally, the routines are meant to be portable in the sense that they will exist in compatible form on any system where C exists and that programs which confine themselves to facilities provided by the standard library can be moved from one system to another essentially without change.

8
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:31,000
 We will not try to describe the entire IO library here. We are more interested in showing the essentials of writing C programs that interact with our operating system environment.

9
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:44,000
 Section 7.1, Access to the Standard Library. Each source file that refers to the standard library function must contain the line #includestdio.h near the beginning.

10
00:01:44,000 --> 00:02:02,000
 The file stdio.h defines certain macros and variables used by the IO library. The use of angle brackets, less than and greater than, instead of the usual double quotes, directs the compiler to search for the file in a directory containing the standard header information.

11
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:07,000
 In Unix, this is often somewhere like /user/include.

12
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:30,000
 Furthermore, it may be necessary when loading the program to specify the library explicitly. For example, on the PDP11 Unix system, the command to compile a program would be "cc sourcefilesetc -ls -ls" indicates loading from the standard library.

13
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:36,000
 Section 7.2, Standard Input and Output.

14
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:38,000
 GetChar InputChar.

15
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:51,000
 The simplest input mechanism is to read a character at a time from the standard input, generally the user's terminal or keyboard, with GetChar. GetChar returns the next input character each time it's called.

16
00:02:51,000 --> 00:03:09,000
 In most environments that support C, a file may be substituted for the terminal by using the "less than" convention. If a program "prog" uses GetChar, then the command line "prog less than in" file causes "prog" to read "in" file instead of the terminal or keyboard.

17
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 The switching of input is done in such a way that "prog" is oblivious to the change. In particular, the string "less than in" file is not included in the command line arguments in argv.

18
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 The input switching is also invisible if the input comes from another program, a pipe mechanism.

19
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:39,000
 The command line "otherprog |prog" runs two programs, "otherprog" and "prog", and arranges for the standard input for "prog" to come from the standard output of "otherprog".

20
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:53,000
 GetChar returns the value "eof" when it encounters end of file on whatever input is being read. The standard library defines the symbolic "eof" constant to be -1, with a pound defined in the file "stdio.h".

21
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:01,000
 But text should be written in terms of "eof", not -1, so as to be independent of the specific value.

22
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:12,000
 For output, putChar("C") puts the character "C" on the standard output, which is also by default the terminal, or screen.

23
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:23,000
 The output can be directed to a file by using "greater than". If "prog" uses putChar, "prog > outfile" will write the standard output onto "outfile" instead of the terminal.

24
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:33,000
 On the Unix system, a pipe can also be used. "prog |anotherprog" puts the standard output of "prog" into the standard input of "otherprog".

25
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:38,000
 Again, "prog" is not aware of the redirection.

26
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:46,000
 Output produced by printf also finds its way to the standard output, and calls to putChar and printf may be interleaved.

27
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:52,000
 A surprising number of programs read only one input stream and write only one output stream.

28
00:04:52,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 For such programs, I/O with getChar, putChar, and printf may be entirely adequate, and is certainly enough to get started.

29
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:07,000
 This is particularly true given file redirection in a pipe file for connecting the output of one program to the input of the next.

30
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 For example, consider the program "lower", which maps its input to lowercase.

31
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:23,000
 This is an example on page 145 of the textbook that you can see at www.cc4e.com/code.

32
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 #include stdio.h, #include ctype.h, main open-paren, closed-paren, open-curly-brace, int c, while open-paren, open-paren, c=getChar, open-paren, closed-paren, closed-paren, not equal to eof, closed-paren, putChar is upper-open-paren, c, closed-paren, question mark, too-lower, open-paren, c, closed-paren, colon, c, closed-paren, semicolon.

33
00:05:52,000 --> 00:06:01,000
 The functions "isUpper" and "tooLower" are actually macros defined in ctype.h.

34
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:07,000
 The macro "isUpper" tests whether its argument is an uppercase letter, returning non-zero if it is and zero if it's not.

35
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:11,000
 The macro "tooLower" converts an uppercase to lowercase letter.

36
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:16,000
 Regardless of how these functions are implemented on a particular machine, their external behavior is the same.

37
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:21,000
 So, programs that use them are shielded from the knowledge of their character set.

38
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:28,000
 To convert multiple files, you can use a program like the Unix Cat to collect files.

39
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:34,000
 Cat file1, file2, dot-dot-dot, vertical bar, lower, greater than, output.

40
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:37,000
 And thus avoid learning how to access files from a program.

41
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:42,000
 The Cat example is presented later as example code in this chapter.

42
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 As an aside, the standard I/O library functions getChar and putChar can actually be macros.

43
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:54,000
 And thus, avoid the overhead of a function call per character.

44
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:58,000
 We'll show how this is done in Chapter 8.

45
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:02,000
 Section 7.3, formatted output, printf.

46
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:12,000
 The two routines printf for output and scanf for input, which we describe in the next section, permit translation to and from character representations of numerical quantities.

47
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:16,000
 They also allow generation or interpretation of formatted lines.

48
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 We've used printf informally throughout the previous chapters.

49
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 Here is a more complete and precise description.

50
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:30,000
 printf, open paren, control, arg1, arg2, etc., close paren.

51
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:38,000
 printf converts formats and prints its arguments on the standard output under the control of the string control.

52
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:53,000
 The control string contains two types of objects, ordinary characters, which are simply copied to the output string, and conversion specifications, each of which causes conversion and printing of the next successive argument to printf.

53
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 Each conversion specification is introduced by the character percent sign and ended by a conversion character.

54
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:10,000
 Between the percent and the conversion character, there may be a minus sign, which specifies left adjustment of the converted argument in its field.

55
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:14,000
 A digit string, specified a minimum field width.

56
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 The converted number will be printed in a field at least this wide and wider if necessary.

57
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:29,000
 If the converted argument has fewer characters than the field, it will be padded on the left or right if the left adjustment indicator has been given to make up the field width.

58
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:36,000
 The padding character is normally blank and zero if the field width is specified with a leading zero.

59
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:39,000
 This zero does not imply an octal field width.

60
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:43,000
 A period, which separates the field width from the next digit string.

61
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 A digit string, that specifies the precision, which specifies the maximum number of characters to be printed from a string or the number of digits to be printed to the right of the decimal point of a float or a double.

62
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:06,000
 A length modifier, the letter L, which indicates that the corresponding data item is a long rather than an int.

63
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:14,000
 The conversion characters and their meanings are D, the argument is converted to decimal notation.

64
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:19,000
 O, the argument is converted to unsigned octal notation without a leading zero.

65
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:25,000
 X, the argument is converted to unsigned hexadecimal notation without a leading zero x.

66
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:29,000
 U, the argument is converted to unsigned decimal notation.

67
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:33,000
 C, the argument is taken to be a single character.

68
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:36,000
 S, the argument is a string.

69
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:45,000
 Characters from the string are printed until a null character is reached or the number of characters indicated by the precision specification is exhausted.

70
00:09:45,000 --> 00:10:02,000
 E, the argument is taken to be a float or a double and converted to decimal notation of the form, optional minus sign, m dot nnn capital E plus or minus xx, where the length of the string of the ends is specified by the precision.

71
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:04,000
 The default precision is 6.

72
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:18,000
 F, the argument is taken to be a float or double and converted to decimal notation of the form, optional minus sign, mm dot nnnn where the length of the string of ends specified by precision.

73
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:20,000
 The default precision is 6.

74
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:27,000
 Note that the precision does not determine the number of significant digits printed in the F format.

75
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:36,000
 G says use percent E or percent F, whichever is shorter, and non-significant zeros are not printed.

76
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:41,000
 If the character after the percent is not a conversion character, the character is simply printed.

77
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:46,000
 Thus, percent may be printed as percent percent.

78
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:51,000
 Most of the format conversions are obvious and have been illustrated in the earlier chapter.

79
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:55,000
 One exception is the precision field as it relates to strings.

80
00:10:55,000 --> 00:11:03,000
 The following table shows the effect of a variety of specifications in printing hello, world, which is 12 characters.

81
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:08,000
 We put colons around each field so you can see its actual width.

82
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:15,000
 Colon percent 10 S colon, colon hello world colon.

83
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 It's 12 characters long, and so we get 12 characters printed because we haven't really told it to strictly limit that.

84
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:28,000
 Colon percent minus 10 S colon, colon hello, comma, world, colon.

85
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:30,000
 No extra spaces.

86
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 Again, 12 characters are used, even though we said 10, it expands it to 12.

87
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:42,000
 And the fact that it's left justified seems our printing more than the width of the field doesn't make any difference.

88
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:50,000
 Colon percent 20 S colon, colon eight spaces, then hello, comma, world, colon.

89
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:56,000
 Eight spaces are put in on the left because it by default is right justified.

90
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:06,000
 Colon percent minus 20 S colon prints colon, hello, comma, world, and then eight spaces and then colon.

91
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 We've told it to left justify, so the eight spaces are added to fill it out to 20 spaces after hello, world.

92
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:24,000
 Colon percent 20 dot 10 S colon gives us colon and then 10 blanks and then hello, comma, world, colon.

93
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 Now in this case, we've told it we really only want 10 characters from the string, and so the LD is truncated.

94
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:43,000
 Percent minus 20 dot 10 S colon, colon, hello, comma, world, and then 10 spaces.

95
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:48,000
 And it's left justified, so the 10 spaces are at the end right before the colon.

96
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:55,000
 Colon percent dot 10 S colon, colon, hello, comma, world, colon.

97
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:03,000
 So now the overall field that's printed is exactly 10 characters, and it is the leftmost 10 characters.

98
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:10,000
 Warning, printf uses its first argument to decide how many arguments follow and what their types are.

99
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:19,000
 It will get confused, and you will get nonsense answers if there are not enough arguments or they are of the wrong type.

100
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:28,000
 As an aside, formatted output is difficult. The design of C printf was inspired by the earlier format statement in Fortran and Alcol.

101
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:34,000
 In order to compete with those languages, C needed to ship with solid support for formatted output.

102
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:38,000
 The approach chosen by C percolated into C-like languages.

103
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:44,000
 PHP and Java simply have a function called printf that mimics most of the C formats.

104
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:48,000
 Python has evolved its approach to formatted output over the years.

105
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:53,000
 An early initial solution had a syntax that used percent to provide C-like formatting.

106
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:58,000
 There was also a format method on the string object.

107
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:05,000
 For example, x equals 421.34.

108
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:16,000
 Print open paren double quote x is percent 7.2f double quote percent open paren x comma close paren close paren.

109
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:23,000
 That uses a percent operator and sends a tuple, but the syntax of percent 7.2f is the same.

110
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:40,000
 Another option is print open paren double quote x is open curly brace y colon 7.2f close curly brace double quote dot format open paren y equals x close paren close paren.

111
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 This sends a set of key value pairs and it's a little clunky.

112
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:53,000
 The latest and least clunky way to do it in modern Python is what we call f-strings.

113
00:14:53,000 --> 00:15:11,000
 And the code is print f double quote print open paren f double quote x is open curly brace x colon 7.2f close curly brace double quote close paren.

114
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:24,000
 But even after all this evolution, much of this output formatting still traces its design inspiration from the C printf capabilities back in 1978.

115
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:27,000
 Formatted input scanf.

116
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:35,000
 The function scanf is the input analog of printf, providing many of the same conversion facilities, but in the opposite direction.

117
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:49,000
 Scanf open paren control, arg1, arg2, etc. close paren. Scanf reads characters from standard input, interprets them according to the format specified in control, and stores the results in the remaining arguments.

118
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:51,000
 The control argument is described below.

119
00:15:51,000 --> 00:16:01,000
 The other arguments, each of which must be a pointer, indicate where the corresponding converted input should be stored.

120
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:08,000
 The control string usually contains conversion specifications, which are used to direct interpretation of input sequences.

121
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:14,000
 The control string may contain blanks, tabs, or new lines. We call these white space characters, which are ignored.

122
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:23,000
 Ordinary characters, not percent, which are expected to match the next non-white space character of the input stream.

123
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:35,000
 Conversion specifications, consisting of the character percent, an optional assignment suppression character asterisk, and an optional number specifying the maximum field width, and a conversion character.

124
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:40,000
 A conversion specification directs the conversion of the next input field.

125
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:54,000
 Normally, the result is placed in the variable pointed to by the corresponding argument. If assignment suppression is indicated by the asterisk character, however, the input field is parsed, but then simply skipped, no assignment is being made.

126
00:16:54,000 --> 00:17:04,000
 An input field is defined as a string of non-white space characters. It extends to either the next white space character, or until the field width, if specified, is exhausted.

127
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:12,000
 This implies that scanf will read across line boundaries to find its input, since new lines are white space.

128
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:21,000
 The conversion character indicates the interpretation of the input field. The corresponding argument must be a pointer, as required by the call-by-value semantics of C.

129
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:24,000
 The following conversion characters are legal.

130
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:31,000
 D. A decimal integer is expected on input. The corresponding argument should be an integer pointer.

131
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:39,000
 O. An octal integer, with or without a leading zero, is expected on input. The corresponding argument should be an integer pointer.

132
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:49,000
 X. A hexadecimal integer, with or without the leading zero x, is expected in the input. The corresponding argument should be an integer pointer.

133
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:57,000
 H. A short integer is expected in the input. The corresponding argument should be a pointer to a short integer.

134
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:06,000
 C. A single character is expected. The corresponding argument should be a character pointer. The next input character is placed at the indicated spot.

135
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:15,000
 The normal skip over white space characters is suppressed in this case. To read the next non-white space character, use %1S.

136
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:28,000
 S. A character string is expected. The corresponding argument should be a character pointer, pointing to an array of characters large enough to accept the string, and a terminating backslash zero, which will be added.

137
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:35,000
 F. A floating point number is expected. The corresponding argument should be a pointer to a float.

138
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:51,000
 The conversion character E is a synonym for F. The input formats for floats is an optional sign, a string of numbers possibly containing a decimal point, and an optional exponent field containing an upper or lowercase e, followed by possibly a signed integer.

139
00:18:51,000 --> 00:19:13,000
 The conversion characters D, O, and X may be preceded by L to indicate that it is a pointer to a long rather than an int appears in the argument list. Similarly, the conversion characters E or F may be preceded by L to indicate that it is a pointer to a double rather than a float in the argument list.

140
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:27,000
 For example, the call int i float x char name 50 close square bracket close semicolon.

141
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:49,000
 Scan F, %D, %F, %S, &i, &x, name, close parenthesis semicolon, with the input line 25, 54.32e-1 Thompson.

142
00:19:49,000 --> 00:20:07,000
 We'll assign the value 25 to i, the value 5.432 to x, and the string Thompson, properly terminated with a z backslash zero, to name. The three input fields may be separated by as many blanks, tabs, and new lines as desired.

143
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:34,000
 The call int i float x char name 50 close square bracket semicolon. Scan F, %2D, %F, %*D, %2S, &i, &x, name, close parenthesis.

144
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:56,000
 With input 56789 0123 45A72 will assign 56 to i, 789.0 to x. Skip over 0123 and place the string 45 in name.

145
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:01,000
 The next call to any input routine will begin searching at the letter A.

146
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:09,000
 In these two examples, name is a pointer and thus must not be preceded by an ampersand.

147
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:36,000
 As another example, the rudimentary calculator of Chapter 4 can now be written with Scan F to do the input/put conversion. This is example code on page 150, the textbook, which you can see at www.cc4e.com/code.

148
00:21:36,000 --> 00:22:03,000
 While open paren, scan F open paren, %LF, &V, not equal EOF, print F, %T, %.2F, sum+=V, semicolon, close curly brace.

149
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:11,000
 Scan F stops when it exhausts its control string or when some input fails to match the control specification.

150
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:21,000
 It returns, as its function residual value, the number of successfully matched and assigned input items. This can be used to decide how many input items were found.

151
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:30,000
 On end of file, EOF is returned. Note that this is different from 0, which means that the next input character does not match the first specification in the control string.

152
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:37,000
 The next call to scan F resumes searching immediately after the last character already returned.

153
00:22:37,000 --> 00:23:03,000
 A final warning, the arguments to scan F must be pointers. By far, the most common error is writing scan F open paren, %D, %, N, semicolon, instead of scan F open paren, %D, &N, semicolon.

154
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:07,000
 Section 7.5, in-memory format conversion.

155
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:18,000
 The functions scanF and printF have siblings called sscanF and sprintf, which perform the corresponding conversion but operate on a string instead of a file.

156
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:36,000
 The general format is sprintf, string, control, arg1, arg2, sscanF, string, control, arg1, arg2, etc.

157
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:46,000
 sprintf formats the arguments in arg1, arg2, etc. according to control as before, but it places the result in a string instead of on the standard output.

158
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:49,000
 Of course, string had better be big enough to receive the result.

159
00:23:49,000 --> 00:24:10,000
 As an example, if the name is a character array and N is an integer, then sprintf, name, %D, ,N, semicolon, creates a string of the form, .NNN, where NNN is the value for N.

160
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:18,000
 sscanF does the reverse conversion. It scans the string according to the format in control and places the results in arg1, arg2, etc.

161
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:21,000
 These arguments must be pointer.

162
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:40,000
 The sscanF, name, %D, ,N, semicolon, sets N to the value of the digits following TEMP in name.

163
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:52,000
 Section 7.6, file access. As an aside, the next two sections do a nice job of covering file input and the notion of the standard error with simple sample code.

164
00:24:52,000 --> 00:25:00,000
 But the authors are also making a subtle point about Unix and how the design of C makes it easy to build Unix utilities.

165
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:11,000
 By the end of section 7.6, we see a 29-line program that is pretty much a complete implementation of the core functionality of the Unix cat command.

166
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:22,000
 Part of the philosophy of Unix was to build commands that are each simple building blocks that can be composed using standard input, standard output, redirection, as well as pipes.

167
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:28,000
 These next two sections are a gentle celebration of the design principles that underlie the Unix operating system.

168
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:38,000
 Also, while we're talking about the linkage between C and Unix, there is a Unix-related Easter egg earlier in the chapter. See if you can find it.

169
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:44,000
 Bonus points if you already noticed it.

170
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:54,000
 The programs written so far have all read the standard input and written the standard output, which we have assumed are magically predefined for a program by the local operating system.

171
00:25:54,000 --> 00:26:00,000
 The next step in I/O is to write a program that accesses a file which is not already connected to the program.

172
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:08,000
 One program that clearly illustrates the need for such operations is Cat, which concatenates a set of name files onto standard output.

173
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:17,000
 Cat is used for printing files on a terminal and is a general-purpose input collector for programs which do not have the capability of accessing files by name.

174
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:26,000
 For example, the command cat x.c y.c prints the contents of the files x.c and y.c on the standard output.

175
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:36,000
 The question is how to arrange for the named files to be read, that is, how to connect the external names that the user thinks of to the statements which actually read the data.

176
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:43,000
 The rules are simple. Before it can be read or written, a file has to be opened by the standard library function fopen.

177
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:53,000
 fopen takes an external name, like x.c or y.c, does some housekeeping and negotiating with the operating system, some details of which do not need to concern us,

178
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:59,000
 and returns an internal name which then must be used for subsequent reads or writes of the file.

179
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:07,000
 The internal name is actually a pointer, called the file pointer, to a structure which contains information about the file, such as the location of a buffer,

180
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:13,000
 the current character position in the buffer, whether the file is being read or written, and the similar.

181
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:23,000
 Users don't need to know the details, because part of the standard I/O definitions are obtained from stdio.h, and it's a structured definition called file.

182
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:34,000
 The only declaration needed for a file pointer is exemplified by file *fopen, open paren, close paren, comma, *fp, semicol.

183
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:41,000
 That says that fp is a pointer to a file, and fopen returns a pointer to a file.

184
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:47,000
 Note that file is a type name, like int, not a structure tag. It's implemented as a typedef.

185
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:53,000
 Details on how all this works on the Unix system are given in Chapter 8.

186
00:27:53,000 --> 00:28:04,000
 The actual call to fopen in a program is fp = fopen, open paren, name, comma, mode, close paren, semicolon.

187
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:08,000
 The first argument of fopen is the name of the file as a character string.

188
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:15,000
 The second argument is the mode, also a character string, which indicates how one intends to use the files.

189
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:21,000
 Allowable modes are read, r, write, w, or append, a.

190
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:27,000
 If you open a file, which does not exist for writing or appending, it is created if possible.

191
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:32,000
 Opening an existing file for writing causes the old constants to be discarded.

192
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:35,000
 Trying to read a file that does not exist is an error.

193
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:41,000
 And there may be other causes of error as well, like trying to read a file when you don't have permission.

194
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:50,000
 If there is any error, fopen will return the null pointer with a value of null, which, for convenience, is also defined in stdio.h.

195
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:55,000
 The next thing needed is a way to read or write the file once it is open.

196
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:00,000
 There are several possibilities, of which getc and putc are the simplest.

197
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:03,000
 getc returns the next character from a file.

198
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:06,000
 It needs the file pointer to tell what file.

199
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:18,000
 Thus, c = getc, open paren, fp, close paren, places in c the next character from the file referenced by fp, and eof when it reaches end of file.

200
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:21,000
 putc is the inverse of getc.

201
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:29,000
 putc, open paren, c, fp, close paren, puts the character c on the file fp and returns c.

202
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:34,000
 Like getchar and putchar, getc and putc may be macros instead of functions.

203
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:41,000
 When a program is started, three files are automatically opened, and file pointers are provided for them.

204
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:54,000
 These files are the standard input, the standard output, and the standard error output. The corresponding file pointers are called stdin, stdout, and stderr.

205
00:29:54,000 --> 00:30:03,000
 Normally, these are all connected to the terminal, but stdin and stdout may be redirected to files or pipes, as described in section 7.2.

206
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:11,000
 getchar and putchar can be defined in terms of getc, putc, stdin, and stdout as follows.

207
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:27,000
 #define getchar, open paren, close paren; getc, open paren, stdin, close paren; #define putchar, open paren, c, close paren; putc, open paren, c, stdout, close paren.

208
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:36,000
 For formatted input or output files, the function fscanf and fprintf may be used. These are identical to scanf and printf.

209
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:47,000
 Save that the first argument is a file pointer that specifies the file to be read or written. The second argument is the control string.

210
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:55,000
 With these preliminaries out of the way, we are now in a position to write the program cat to concatenate files.

211
00:30:55,000 --> 00:31:02,000
 The basic design is one that has been found convenient for many programs. If there are command-like arguments, they are processed in order.

212
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:11,000
 If there are no arguments, the standard input is processed. This way the program can be used standalone or part of a larger process.

213
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:22,000
 This example is on page 153 of the textbook, and you can see it at www.cc4e.com/code.

